Thank you Ralph,<br><br>I found the problem. it is because I wrongly configured the second node&#39;s selinux property (which is set to be enforced).<br>After it is disabled, the parallel-hello works fine.<br><br>regards,<br>
-andria<br><br><br><div class="gmail_quote">On Tue, Mar 17, 2009 at 8:08 PM, Ralph Castain <span dir="ltr">&lt;<a href="mailto:rhc@lanl.gov">rhc@lanl.gov</a>&gt;</span> wrote:<br><blockquote class="gmail_quote" style="border-left: 1px solid rgb(204, 204, 204); margin: 0pt 0pt 0pt 0.8ex; padding-left: 1ex;">
Hi Andria<br>
<br>
The problem is a permissions one - your system has been setup so that only root has permission to open a TCP socket. I don&#39;t know what system you are running - you might want to talk to your system admin or someone knowledgeable on that operating system to ask them how to revise the required permissions.<br>

<br>
Ralph<div><div></div><div class="h5"><br>
<br>
